18 Existing law provides a tenant with a defense in a summary proceeding or
19 action for possession of a dwelling if the landlord’s attempt to terminate the
20 tenancy or regain possession violates certain provisions that prohibit discriminatory
21 housing practices. (NRS 118.115) Section 3 of this bill applies this provision to a
22 violation of section 1.
23 Existing law authorizes a person to file an action in any district court of this
24 State to enforce certain provisions that prohibit discriminatory housing practices. If
25 the plaintiff prevails, the court may award to the plaintiff actual damages, punitive
26 damages, court costs and a reasonable attorney’s fee. (NRS 118.120) Section 4 of
27 this bill authorizes a person to enforce the provisions of section 1 by filing such an
28 action.
29 Existing law prohibits a landlord from taking certain retaliatory actions against
30 a tenant who has complained in good faith to certain persons or entities of a
31 violation of the Nevada Fair Housing Law. (NRS 118A.510) Section 5 of this bill
32 applies this provision to a violation of section 1.
33 Under existing law, a person who claims to have been injured by a
34 discriminatory housing practice is authorized to file a complaint with the Nevada
35 Equal Rights Commission. (NRS 118.110) Under this bill, a person who claims to
36 have been injured by a violation of section 1 is also authorized to file a complaint.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. Chapter 118 of NRS is hereby amended by adding
2 thereto a new section to read as follows:
3 1. A landlord shall not refuse to rent or refuse to negotiate
4 for the rental of, or otherwise make unavailable or deny, a
5 dwelling to a corporation that rents a dwelling on behalf of a
6 person with a disability solely because the corporation provides
7 assistance in obtaining housing to a person with a disability.
8 2. If such a corporation applies for an available dwelling on
9 behalf of a person with a disability and the application is denied,
10 the landlord shall submit to the corporation, the Aging and
11 Disability Services Division of the Department of Health and
12 Human Services and the Office of the Ombudsman for Owners in
13 Common-Interest Communities and Condominium Hotels a
14 written explanation of the reasons for the denial within 7 days
15 after the denial.
